  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the best free web hosting provider?",
  "response": "Choosing the best free web hosting provider can depend on your specific needs and requirements, but here are some popular options that are highly regarded in the hosting community:\n\n1. **InfinityFree**:\n   - *Features*: Unlimited disk space and bandwidth, free subdomain, no ads, and Free SSL on all websites.\n   - *Pros*: Offers an ad-free experience and supports PHP and MySQL.\n   - *Cons*: Limited technical support and certain limitations on features and access.\n\n2. **000webhost**:\n   - *Features*: 1 GB disk space, 10 GB bandwidth, free subdomains, and 1 MySQL database.\n   - *Pros*: User-friendly interface and reliable uptime.\n   - *Cons*: Displays ads on your site and limitations on resources for free accounts.\n\n3. **ByetHost**:\n   - *Features*: 5 GB disk space, unlimited bandwidth, free subdomains, and MySQL databases.\n   - *Pros*: Ad-free hosting and fairly generous resource allocation.\n   - *Cons*: Customer support can be slow for free users.\n\n4. **AwardSpace**:\n   - *Features*: 1 GB disk space, 5 GB bandwidth, free domain, 1 MySQL database.\n   - *Pros*: No ads, free domain with options for further upgrading.\n   - *Cons*: Limited storage and bandwidth compared to other options.\n\n5. **FreeHosting**:\n   - *Features*: 10 GB disk space, unmetered bandwidth, and 1 email account.\n   - *Pros*: Ads-free with generous bandwidth.\n   - *Cons*: Limited storage and support.\n\n6. **Google Firebase**:\n   - *Features*: Free tier with generous usage limits, hosting on Google's reliable infrastructure.\n   - *Pros*: Great for developers looking to build mobile apps and websites.\n   - *Cons*: Learning curve can be higher compared to traditional web hosting services.\n\nThese providers offer a range of features and capabilities, so it's worth comparing them based on what you need for your website. If you're just starting out and require basic functionality, these options can be effective for hobby projects, personal blogs, or learning purposes. If you require more robust features or plan on scaling your website in the future, you may eventually need to consider paid hosting options.",
